Shakespeare presents fate as real and inescapable, despite Macbeth’s attempts to change it. For example,
when Macbeth orders Fleance’s murder, Fleance escapes unharmed. Macbeth is therefore unsuccessful
in his attempt to defy the prophecy that says Banquo’s descendants will be kings. Macbeth’s failure
reects a common belief in Shakespearean times about how certain people were fated to rule.
However, by the end of the play, Macbeth seems to accept that he cannot control fate. In his nal
soliloquy he describes life as “a poor player”. This metaphor shows how Macbeth thinks that people are
as powerless as actors following direction. This suggests that he thinks free will does not exist and that
his life is dictated by forces beyond his control.
In the last act, Shakespeare shows how Macbeth’s belief in fate has become a blind belief in his invincibility.
Despite being aware that the prophecy about Birnam Wood was deliberately misleading, Macbeth still
doesn’t acknowledge that the phrase “born of woman” could be interpreted in different ways. His belief in
his invincibility makes him unable to consider alternative meanings of the Witches’ predictions.
Macbeth’s inconsistent attitude towards fate emphasises the difculty he has in trusting the prophecies.
On the one hand, Macbeth believes that his fate as King is determined, which is seen when he says
“Come what come may”. However, he frequently attempts to exercise his free will to full or prevent
the prophecies, such as when he has Banquo murdered. There was a widespread belief about fate
when the play was written: . Macbeth’s internal conict means that he both conforms to and
contradicts this view, so his attitude to fate would have seemed complex to an Elizabethan audience.
b)In the extract, Macbeth reacts to the prophecies about his fate.
Write about attitudes to fate in the rest of the play.
Shakespeare presents Banquo’s attitude towards fate as more cynical than Macbeth’s. In Act 1, Scene 3,
Banquo tells Macbeth that he’s worried the Witches are tricking them, saying they are “instruments of
darkness”. This shows his scepticism towards the fate prophesied for his descendants. However, Fleance
later escapes from the murderers, suggesting that a character’s attitude to fate is irrelevant, as the
prophecy about Banquo’s descendants may be coming true regardless of his opinion.
